Events.html: 915 – Pope John X crowned Berengar I of Italy as Holy Roman Emperor.

Events.html: 1799 – War of the Second Coalition: Battle of Wiesloch – Austrian Lieutenant Field Marshal Sztáray de Nagy-Mihaly defeats the French at Wiesloch.
Events.text: War of the Second Coalition: Battle of Wiesloch – Austrian Lieutenant Field Marshal Sztáray de Nagy-Mihaly defeats the French at Wiesloch.

Events.html: 1800 – War of the Second Coalition: Battle of Hohenlinden – French General Moreau decisively defeats the Austrian Archduke John near Munich. Coupled with First Consul Napoleon Bonaparte's earlier victory at Marengo, this will force the Austrians to sign an armistice and end the war.
Events.text: War of the Second Coalition: Battle of Hohenlinden – French General Moreau decisively defeats the Austrian Archduke John near Munich. Coupled with First Consul Napoleon Bonaparte's earlier victory at Marengo, this will force the Austrians to sign an armistice and end the war.

Events.html: 1818 – Illinois becomes the 21st U.S. state.
Events.text: Illinois becomes the 21st U.S. state.

Events.html: 1834 – The Zollverein (German Customs Union) begins the first regular census in Germany.
Events.text: The Zollverein (German Customs Union) begins the first regular census in Germany.

Events.html: 1854 – Battle of the Eureka Stockade: More than 20 gold miners at Ballarat, Victoria, are killed by state troopers in an uprising over mining licences.
Events.text: Battle of the Eureka Stockade: More than 20 gold miners at Ballarat, Victoria, are killed by state troopers in an uprising over mining licences.

Events.html: 1898 – The Duquesne Country and Athletic Club defeated an all-star collection of early football players 16-0, in what is considered to be the very first all-star game for professional American football.

Events.html: 1901 – In a State of the Union message, U.S. President Theodore Roosevelt asks Congress to curb the power of trusts "within reasonable limits".
Events.text: In a State of the Union message, U.S. President Theodore Roosevelt asks Congress to curb the power of trusts "within reasonable limits".

Events.html: 1904 – The Jovian moon Himalia is discovered by Charles Dillon Perrine at California's Lick Observatory.
Events.text: The Jovian moon Himalia is discovered by Charles Dillon Perrine at California's Lick Observatory.

Events.html: 1910 – Modern neon lighting is first demonstrated by Georges Claude at the Paris Motor Show.
Events.text: Modern neon lighting is first demonstrated by Georges Claude at the Paris Motor Show.

Events.html: 1912 – Bulgaria, Greece, Montenegro, and Serbia (the Balkan League) sign an armistice with the Ottoman Empire, temporarily halting the First Balkan War. (The armistice will expire on February 3, 1913, and hostilities will resume.)
Events.text: Bulgaria, Greece, Montenegro, and Serbia (the Balkan League) sign an armistice with the Ottoman Empire, temporarily halting the First Balkan War. (The armistice will expire on February 3, 1913, and hostilities will resume.)

Events.html: 1919 – After nearly 20 years of planning and construction, including two collapses causing 89 deaths, the Quebec Bridge opens to traffic.
Events.text: After nearly 20 years of planning and construction, including two collapses causing 89 deaths, the Quebec Bridge opens to traffic.

Events.html: 1925 – World War I aftermath: The final Locarno Treaty is signed in London, establishing post-war territorial settlements.
Events.text: World War I aftermath: The final Locarno Treaty is signed in London, establishing post-war territorial settlements.

Events.html: 1927 – Putting Pants on Philip, the first Laurel and Hardy film, is released.
Events.text: Putting Pants on Philip, the first Laurel and Hardy film, is released.

Events.html: 1944 – Greek Civil War: Fighting breaks out in Athens between the ELAS and government forces supported by the British Army.
Events.text: Greek Civil War: Fighting breaks out in Athens between the ELAS and government forces supported by the British Army.

Events.html: 1959 – The current flag of Singapore is adopted, six months after Singapore became self-governing within the British Empire.
Events.text: The current flag of Singapore is adopted, six months after Singapore became self-governing within the British Empire.

Events.html: 1960 – The musical Camelot debuts at the Majestic Theatre on Broadway. It will become associated with the Kennedy administration.
Events.text: The musical Camelot debuts at the Majestic Theatre on Broadway. It will become associated with the Kennedy administration.

Events.html: 1964 – Free Speech Movement: Police arrest over 800 students at the University of California, Berkeley, following their takeover and sit-in at the administration building in protest of the UC Regents' decision to forbid protests on UC property.

Events.html: 1967 – At Groote Schuur Hospital in Cape Town, South Africa, a transplant team headed by Christiaan Barnard carries out the first heart transplant on a human (53-year-old Louis Washkansky).
Events.text: At Groote Schuur Hospital in Cape Town, South Africa, a transplant team headed by Christiaan Barnard carries out the first heart transplant on a human (53-year-old Louis Washkansky).

Events.html: 1971 – Indo-Pakistani War of 1971: Pakistan launches a pre-emptive strike against India and a full scale war begins claiming hundreds of lives.
Events.text: Indo-Pakistani War of 1971: Pakistan launches a pre-emptive strike against India and a full scale war begins claiming hundreds of lives.

Events.html: 1973 – Pioneer program: Pioneer 10 sends back the first close-up images of Jupiter.
Events.text: Pioneer program: Pioneer 10 sends back the first close-up images of Jupiter.

Events.html: 1976 – An assassination attempt is made on Bob Marley. He is shot twice, but will play a concert only two days later.
Events.text: An assassination attempt is made on Bob Marley. He is shot twice, but will play a concert only two days later.

Events.html: 1979 – In Cincinnati, Ohio, 11 fans are suffocated in a crush for seats on the concourse outside Riverfront Coliseum before a Who concert.
Events.text: In Cincinnati, Ohio, 11 fans are suffocated in a crush for seats on the concourse outside Riverfront Coliseum before a Who concert.

Events.html: 1979 – Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini becomes the first Supreme Leader of Iran.
Events.text: Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini becomes the first Supreme Leader of Iran.

Events.html: 1982 – A soil sample is taken from Times Beach, Missouri, that will be found to contain 300 times the safe level of dioxin.
Events.text: A soil sample is taken from Times Beach, Missouri, that will be found to contain 300 times the safe level of dioxin.

Events.html: 1984 – Bhopal Disaster: A methyl isocyanate leak from a Union Carbide pesticide plant in Bhopal, India, kills more than 3,800 people outright and injures 150,000–600,000 others (some 6,000 of whom would later die from their injuries) in one of the worst industrial disasters in history.

Events.html: 1989 – Cold War: In a meeting off the coast of Malta, U.S. President George H. W. Bush and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev release statements indicating that the cold war between NATO and the Soviet Union may be coming to an end.
Events.text: Cold War: In a meeting off the coast of Malta, U.S. President George H. W. Bush and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev release statements indicating that the cold war between NATO and the Soviet Union may be coming to an end.

Events.html: 1990 – At Detroit Metropolitan Airport, Northwest Airlines Flight 1482 collides with Northwest Airlines Flight 299 on the runway, killing seven passengers and one crew member aboard flight 1482.
Events.text: At Detroit Metropolitan Airport, Northwest Airlines Flight 1482 collides with Northwest Airlines Flight 299 on the runway, killing seven passengers and one crew member aboard flight 1482.

Events.html: 1992 – UN Security Council Resolution 794 is unanimously passed, approving a coalition of United Nations peacekeepers led by the United States to form UNITAF, with the task of establishing peace and ensuring that humanitarian aid is distributed in Somalia.
Events.text: UN Security Council Resolution 794 is unanimously passed, approving a coalition of United Nations peacekeepers led by the United States to form UNITAF, with the task of establishing peace and ensuring that humanitarian aid is distributed in Somalia.

Events.html: 1992 – The Greek oil tanker Aegean Sea, carrying 80,000 tonnes of crude oil, runs aground in a storm while approaching La Coruña, Spain, and spills much of its cargo.

Events.html: 1992 – A test engineer for Sema Group uses a personal computer to send the world's first text message via the Vodafone network to the phone of a colleague.

Events.html: 1997 – In Ottawa, Canada, representatives from 121 countries sign the Ottawa Treaty prohibiting manufacture and deployment of anti-personnel landmines. The United States, People's Republic of China, and Russia do not sign the treaty, however.
